<heading id="5363761CA261B056FEFD27F7FDABFF2C" bold="true" box="[262,602,190,213]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" reason="2">
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A261B056FEFD27F7FDABFF2C" authority="(Roding, 1798)" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[262,602,190,213]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="noae">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FEFD27F7FDABFF2C" bold="true" box="[262,602,190,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FEFD27F7FE59FF2C" bold="true" box="[262,424,190,213]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Tridacna noae</emphasis>
(Röding, 1798)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="082BC170A261B056FF8A27B7FBB8FEEC" blockId="6.[113,752,254,629]" lastBlockId="6.[812,1451,190,277]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FF8A27B7FF4AFEEC" bold="true" box="[113,187,254,277]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Types.</emphasis>
Species figures were provided in 
<bibRefCitation id="6C05BC81A261B056FDC127B7FD1AFEEC" author="Chemnitz JH" box="[570,747,254,277]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" pagination="111 - 124" refId="ref6324" refString="Chemnitz JH (1784) Neues systematiches Conchylien Cabinet. Band 7. G. N. Raspe, Nurnberg, pp. 111 - 124." type="book chapter" year="1784">Chemnitz, 1784</bibRefCitation>
, vol. 7, pl. 49, fig. 494 and 
<bibRefCitation id="6C05BC81A261B056FE682657FDC3FECC" author="McLean RA" box="[403,562,286,309]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref6747" refString="McLean RA (1947) A revision of the pelecypod family Tridacnidae. Notulae Naturae, Number 195: 1 - 7." type="book chapter" year="1947">McLean, 1947</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 12. Since no type material is extant and no types have been designated to date, a 
<typeStatus id="D72F7FD2A261B056FF182617FEC6FE8C" box="[227,311,350,373]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">neotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A261B056FE9A2617FE0EFE8C" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[353,511,350,373]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="noae">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FE9A2617FE0EFE8C" box="[353,511,350,373]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Tridacna noae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is hereby designated. The 
<typeStatus id="D72F7FD2A261B056FF5F2637FF09FE6C" box="[164,248,382,405]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">neotype</typeStatus>
specimen (length 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FE3D2637FDDAFE6C" box="[454,555,382,405]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.44" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="94.4">94.4 mm</quantity>
; height 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FD7E2637FD19FE6C" box="[645,744,382,405]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.84" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="58.4">58.4 mm</quantity>
) was collected on 
<date id="7C2AE7B0A261B056FEC526D7FE04FE4C" box="[318,501,414,437]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" value="2007-08-28">28 August 2007</date>
by Jhih-Hui Hung at Naliao, Green Island, 
<collectingCountry id="708381E0A261B056FE9226F7FE4AFE2C" box="[361,443,446,469]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
. The specimen is deposited in the National Museum of Natural Science, 
<collectingCountry id="708381E0A261B056FD992697FD42FE0C" box="[610,691,478,501]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, with catalogue number NMNS-6928-001 (
<figureCitation id="90AFDDF5A261B056FDF226B7FD70FDEC" box="[521,641,510,533]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[113,148,2062,2083]" captionTargetBox="[116,1449,493,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-17@8.[107,1449,464,2049]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 6. Shell morphology of Tridacna maxima from Hongchia with prominent rib scales on right valve (A–F) and Tridacna noae from Naliao (G–L). R: rib; S: scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353474/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Fig. 6G–L</figureCitation>
). The soft body parts were preserved in 70% alcohol. Two additional specimens (NMNS-6928-002, length, 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FDCB2577FD60FDAC" box="[560,657,574,597]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.79" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="97.9">97.9mm</quantity>
; height, 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FF8A2517FF3DFD8C" box="[113,204,606,629]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="52.5">52.5mm</quantity>
and NMNS-6928-003, length, 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FDCE2517FD65FD8C" box="[565,660,606,629]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.77" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="87.7">87.7mm</quantity>
; height, 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FCD727F7FC77FF2C" box="[812,902,190,213]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.56" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="mm" value="45.6">45.6mm</quantity>
) were collected on 
<date id="7C2AE7B0A261B056FBA527F7FAD3FF2C" box="[1118,1314,190,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" value="2008-11-01">1 November 2008</date>
by Jhih-Hui Hung at Chuanfanshr, 
<collectingCountry id="708381E0A261B056FBDB2797FB9FFF0C" box="[1056,1134,222,245]" name="Taiwan" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
and the soft body parts were preserved in 70% alcohol.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="408E92FBA261B057FCD72677FE36FEED" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="131" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" type="description">
<paragraph id="082BC170A261B057FCD72677FE36FEED" blockId="6.[812,1452,318,629]" lastBlockId="7.[136,775,189,276]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="131" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FCD72677FC49FEAC" bold="true" box="[812,952,318,341]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Description.</emphasis>
Shell inflated, strongly inequilateral, usually elongate-ovate. Shell length commonly between 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A261B056FA882617FCA0FE6C" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" unit="cm" value="13.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="6.0">6–20 cm</quantity>
. Umbo markedly anterior in position, margin with a moderately wide byssal orifice. Shell has 5–7 radial ribs, mostly 6, with round to sharp projections on the upper margins. Scales are relatively abundant and the intervals between them on each rib are narrow. In the living animal, mantle colours vary considerably from brilliant to subdued brown yellow, bluish green, blackish blue, blue, and brown. The mantle pattern has one to several obvious layers of oval patches bounded by white margins. Black hyaline organs (eyes) along the border of the mantle are relatively sparse forming a discontinuous line.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="5CEB91F8A261B056FF8A2F58FE29F7BB" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353470" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5353470" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353470/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" startId="6.[113,148,2065,2086]" targetBox="[235,1329,683,2036]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph id="082BC170A261B056FF8A2F58FE29F7BB" blockId="6.[113,1452,2065,2114]" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">
Fig. 4. Neighbour joining tree of 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A261B056FE382F58FDC4F7DF" authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1819" box="[451,565,2065,2086]" pageId="6" pageNumber="124" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tridacninae">Tridacninae</taxonomicName>
using Kimura 2-parameter model based on 18S rRNA gene sequence. Bootstrap values: 1,000; outgroup: 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A261B056FEE02F64FE23F7BB" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[283,466,2093,2114]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Corculum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="6" pageNumber="130" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cardissa">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A261B056FEE02F64FE23F7BB" box="[283,466,2093,2114]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="130">Corculum cardissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="408E92FBA260B057FF732674FDC4FE0D" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="082BC170A260B057FF732674FDC4FE0D" blockId="7.[136,775,317,500]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FF732674FE35FEAD" bold="true" box="[136,452,317,340]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
Known from northern and Southern 
<collectingCountry id="708381E0A260B057FF162614FECFFE8D" box="[237,318,349,372]" name="Taiwan" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
, Orchid Island, Green Island, Hsiaoliuchiu, 
<collectingRegion id="CA500F92A260B057FF732634FF29FE6D" box="[136,216,381,404]" country="Taiwan" name="Penghu" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Penghu</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="90AFDDF5A260B057FF1E2634FED2FE6D" box="[229,291,381,404]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[834,869,2090,2111]" captionTargetBox="[835,1479,1240,2065]" captionTargetId="figure-483@1.[825,1485,1232,2078]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. Map of Taiwan showing sampling sites for giant clams." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353464" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353464/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="6C05BC81A260B057FED52634FE55FE6D" author="Tang YC" box="[302,420,381,404]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" refId="ref7139" refString="Tang YC (2005) The systematic status of Tridacna maxima (Bivalvia: Tridacnidae) based on morphological and molecular evidence. Unpublished MSc thesis, National Taiwan Ocean University, Keelung, 114 pp." type="book" year="2005">Tang, 2005</bibRefCitation>
and this study), 
<collectingRegion id="CA500F92A260B057FDB42634FD43FE6D" box="[591,690,381,404]" country="Japan" name="Okinawa" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Okinawa</collectingRegion>
, and the Ishigaki Islands of 
<collectingCountry id="708381E0A260B057FEAC26D4FE65FE4D" box="[343,404,413,436]" name="Japan" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="6C05BC81A260B057FE5826D4FD8DFE4D" author="Kubo H &amp; Iwai K" box="[419,636,413,436]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" pagination="205 - 210" refId="ref6610" refString="Kubo H &amp; Iwai K (2007) On sympatric two species within Tridacna &quot; maxima &quot;. Annual Report of Okinawa Fishery and Ocean Research Center, 68: 205 - 210." type="journal article" year="2007">Kubo &amp; Iwai, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Individuals are attached by a byssus and bore into coral, living in littoral and shallow waters to a depth of 
<specimenCount id="1E920AF9A260B057FE0D2694FDC4FE0D" box="[502,565,477,500]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" type="generic">
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A260B057FE0D2694FDC0FE0D" box="[502,561,477,500]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" unit="m" value="20.0">20 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="408E92FBA260B057FF732554FDBAFC2D" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="082BC170A260B057FF732554FDBAFC2D" blockId="7.[136,775,541,980]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FF732554FF04FDCD" bold="true" box="[136,245,541,564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Remarks.</emphasis>
The shell of this species (
<figureCitation id="90AFDDF5A260B057FE012554FD99FDCD" box="[506,616,541,564]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[113,148,2062,2083]" captionTargetBox="[116,1449,493,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-17@8.[107,1449,464,2049]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 6. Shell morphology of Tridacna maxima from Hongchia with prominent rib scales on right valve (A–F) and Tridacna noae from Naliao (G–L). R: rib; S: scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353474/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Fig. 6G–L</figureCitation>
) is very similar in general appearance to 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FE5F2574FD95FDAD" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[420,612,573,596]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FE5F2574FD95FDAD" box="[420,612,573,596]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Tridacna maxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., NMNS- 6928-004, length, 93.0 mm; height, 
<quantity id="CF6C6C95A260B057FDF42514FD81FD8D" box="[527,624,605,628]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.7299999999999995" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" unit="mm" value="77.3">77.3 mm</quantity>
) (
<figureCitation id="90AFDDF5A260B057FD7C2514FD0DFD8D" box="[647,764,605,628]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[113,148,2062,2083]" captionTargetBox="[116,1449,493,2036]" captionTargetId="figure-17@8.[107,1449,464,2049]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 6. Shell morphology of Tridacna maxima from Hongchia with prominent rib scales on right valve (A–F) and Tridacna noae from Naliao (G–L). R: rib; S: scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353474" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353474/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Fig. 6A–F</figureCitation>
). Both species are extremely variable in outline as well as in the number and form of the ribs, and the abundance and shape of the scales. Key characters that distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FD4C25F4FCF6FD2D" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[695,775,701,724]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="noae">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FD4C25F4FCF6FD2D" box="[695,775,701,724]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">T. noae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FF432594FEDAFD0D" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[184,299,733,756]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FF432594FF36FD0D" box="[184,199,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FF2C2594FEDAFD0D" box="[215,299,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">maxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the mantle pattern and the appearance/ arrangement of hyaline organs (eyes). 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FDEF25B4FD3DFCED" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[532,716,765,788]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FDEF25B4FD3DFCED" box="[532,716,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Tridacna maxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
often has a peripheral-banded pattern with a different colour on the mantle margin. However, the mantle pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FD4C2474FCF6FCAD" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[695,775,829,852]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="noae">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FD4C2474FCF6FCAD" box="[695,775,829,852]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">T. noae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by having one to several obvious layers of oval patches bounded by white margins (
<figureCitation id="90AFDDF5A260B057FDB02434FD7EFC6D" box="[587,655,893,916]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[136,171,2063,2084]" captionTargetBox="[135,1481,550,2039]" captionTargetId="figure-45@9.[129,1485,548,2042]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 7. Mantle colour pattern and hyaline organs of Tridacna maxima (A, B) and Tridacna noae (C, D). E, Enlarged hyaline organs of T. maxima; F, Enlarged hyaline organs of T. noae. →: Hyaline organs." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353476" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353476/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The eyes are concentrated as a continuous line along the mantle margin in 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FF5E24F4FF08FC2D" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[165,249,957,980]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="maxima">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FF5E24F4FF08FC2D" box="[165,249,957,980]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">maxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but are discontinuous in 
<taxonomicName id="CF94BAF3A260B057FDEA24F4FDB4FC2D" baseAuthorityName="Roding" baseAuthorityYear="1798" box="[529,581,957,980]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Tridacna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="7" pageNumber="131" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="noae">
<emphasis id="3AE01D62A260B057FDEA24F4FDB4FC2D" box="[529,581,957,980]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="131">noae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
